\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.14}{\ignorespaces The electronic recoil energy spectrum expected from major background sources. While radiation from materials and the double beta decay of \mhchem@ce@xiii {\noexpand ^{\noexpand 1\noexpand 3\noexpand 6}\noexpand X\noexpand e} dominate at high energies, \mhchem@ce@xiii {\noexpand ^{\noexpand 2\noexpand 2\noexpand 2}\noexpand R\noexpand n} dominates at the lowest energies as can be seen here and in Fig.\tmspace +\thinmuskip {.1667em}\ref {fig:xe1t_er_bkg_low}. This low energy region is of the most concern for dark matter searches. Image Credit: Ref.\tmspace +\thinmuskip {.1667em}\cite {aprile2016physics}.}}{76}{figure.3.14}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.15}{\ignorespaces The electronic recoil energy spectrum from background at low energies. Note that under 15 keV, the upper threshold for electronic recoils relevant to the dark matter search, \mhchem@ce@xiii {\noexpand ^{\noexpand 2\noexpand 2\noexpand 2}\noexpand R\noexpand n}{} is the dominant source of electronic recoils. Image Credit: Ref.\tmspace +\thinmuskip {.1667em}\cite {aprile2016physics}.}}{76}{figure.3.15}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.16}{\ignorespaces The \mhchem@ce@xiii {\noexpand ^{\noexpand 2\noexpand 3\noexpand 8}\noexpand U}{} (left) and \mhchem@ce@xiii {\noexpand ^{\noexpand 2\noexpand 3\noexpand 2}\noexpand T\noexpand h}{} (right) decay chains. The \mhchem@ce@xiii {\noexpand ^{\noexpand 2\noexpand 3\noexpand 8}\noexpand U}{} chain ultimately produces an intrinsic and the largest background source of electronic recoils in XENON1T while the \mhchem@ce@xiii {\noexpand ^{\noexpand 2\noexpand 3\noexpand 2}\noexpand T\noexpand h}{} chain results in a very useful electronic recoil calibration source. Image Credit: Berkely Nuclear Forensics Group.}}{78}{figure.3.16}
